Detailed Description

A heap protocol, suitable for use with many variations of the heap structure.

Objects are "heapified" according to their sorted order, so they must respond to the -compare: selector, which accepts another object and returns NSOrderedAscending, NSOrderedSame, or NSOrderedDescending (constants in NSComparisonResult) as the receiver is less than, equal to, or greater than the argument, respectively. (Several Cocoa classes already implement the -compare: method, including NSString, NSDate, NSNumber, NSDecimalNumber, and NSCell.)

Attention:
Due to the nature of a heap and how objects are stored internally, using NSFastEnumeration is not guaranteed to provide the objects in the order in which objects would be removed from the heap. If you want the objects to be sorted without removing them from the heap, use allObjectsInSortedOrder instead.

- (void) addObjectsFromArray: (NSArray *)  anArray

Adds the objects in a given array to the receiver, then re-establish the heap property.

After all the objects have been inserted, objects are "heapified" as necessary, proceeding backwards from index count/2 down to 0.

Parameters:
anArrayAn array of objects to add to the receiver.

- (NSArray*) allObjectsInSortedOrder

Returns an array containing the objects in this heap in sorted order.

Returns:
An array containing the objects in this heap in sorted order. If the heap is empty, the array is also empty.
Attention:
Since only the first object in a heap is guaranteed to be in sorted order, this method incurs extra costs of (1) time for sorting the contents and (2) memory for storing an extra array. However, it does not affect the order of elements in the heap itself.

- (id) initWithArray: (NSArray *)  anArray

Initialize a heap with ascending ordering and objects from a given array.

Objects are added to the heap as they occur in the array, then "heapified" with an ordering of NSOrderedAscending.

Parameters:
anArrayAn array containing objects with which to populate a new heap.
Returns:
An initialized CHHeap that contains the objects in anArray, to be sorted in ascending order.
See also:
- initWithOrdering:array:

Reimplemented in CHBinaryHeap, and CHMutableArrayHeap.

- (id) initWithOrdering: (NSComparisonResult)  order

Initialize a heap with a given sort ordering and no objects.

Parameters:
orderThe sort order to use, either NSOrderedAscending or NSOrderedDescending. The root element of the heap will be the smallest or largest (according to the -compare: method), respectively. For any other value, an NSInvalidArgumentException is raised.
Returns:
An initialized CHHeap that contains no objects and will sort in the specified order.

- (id) initWithOrdering: (NSComparisonResult)  order
array: (NSArray *)  anArray 

Initialize a heap with a given sort ordering and objects from a given array.

Objects are added to the heap as they occur in the array, then "heapified" with an ordering of order.

Parameters:
orderThe sort order to use, either NSOrderedAscending or NSOrderedDescending. The root element of the heap will be the smallest or largest (according to the -compare: method), respectively. For any other value, an NSInvalidArgumentException is raised.
anArrayAn array containing objects with which to populate a new heap.
Returns:
An initialized CHHeap that contains the objects in anArray, to be sorted in the specified order.

Reimplemented in CHBinaryHeap, and CHMutableArrayHeap.

- (BOOL) isEqualToHeap: (id< CHHeap >)  otherHeap

Compares the receiving heap to another heap.

Two heaps have equal contents if they each hold the same number of objects and (when fully sorted) objects at a given position in each heap satisfy the -isEqual: test.

Parameters:
otherHeapA heap.
Returns:
YES if the contents of otherHeap are equal to the contents of the receiver, otherwise NO.

Reimplemented in CHBinaryHeap, and CHMutableArrayHeap.

- (NSEnumerator*) objectEnumerator

Returns an enumerator that accesses each object in the heap in sorted order.

Returns:
An enumerator that accesses each object in the heap in sorted order. The enumerator returned is never nil; if the heap is empty, the enumerator will always return nil for -nextObject and an empty array for -allObjects.
Attention:
Since only the first object in a heap is guaranteed to be in sorted order, this method incurs extra costs of (1) time for sorting the contents and (2) memory for storing an extra array. However, it does not affect the order of elements in the heap itself.
Note:
On platforms that support NSFastEnumeration, that construct will also enumerate objects in sorted order.
Warning:
Modifying a collection while it is being enumerated is unsafe, and may cause a mutation exception to be raised.
See also:
- allObjectsInSortedOrder

Reimplemented in CHBinaryHeap, and CHMutableArrayHeap.
